es represent solutions to linear equations, and their intersection represen=
ts the set of common solutions: in this case, a unique point. The blue line=
 is the common solution to two of these equations. </figcaption></figure>
<p>Linear algebra is central to almost all areas of mathematics. For instan=
ce, linear algebra is fundamental in modern presentations of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geometry</a>, inclu=
ding for defining basic objects such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">lines</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Plane (geometry)">planes</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
otation_(mathematics)" title=3D"Rotation (mathematics)">rotations</a>. Also=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analysis" title=3D"Fu=
nctional analysis">functional analysis</a>, a branch of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis=
">mathematical analysis</a>, may be viewed as the application of linear alg=
ebra to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_of_functions" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Space of functions">function spaces</a>.
</p><p>Linear algebra is also used in most sciences and fields of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engine=
ering</a> because it allows <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathem=
atical_model" title=3D"Mathematical model">modeling</a> many natural phenom=
ena, and computing efficiently with such models. For <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonlinear_system" title=3D"Nonlinear system">nonlinear s=
ystems</a>, which cannot be modeled with linear algebra, it is often used f=
or dealing with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First-order_approx=
imation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"First-order approximation">first-or=
der approximations</a>, using the fact that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Differential_(mathematics)" title=3D"Differential (mathematic=
s)">differential</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivar=
iate_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multivariate function">multiv=
ariate function</a> at a point is the linear map that best approximates the=
 function near that point.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#History" title=3D"Determ=
inant">Determinant =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gaussian_elimination#History" title=3D"Gaussian elimination">=
Gaussian elimination =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></div>
<p>The procedure (using counting rods) for solving simultaneous linear equa=
tions now called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_eliminat=
ion" title=3D"Gaussian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a> appears in the=
 ancient Chinese mathematical text <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Rod_calculus#System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"Rod calculus">Chapter Ei=
ght: <i>Rectangular Arrays</i></a> of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/The_Nine_Chapters_on_the_Mathematical_Art" title=3D"The Nine Chapter=
s on the Mathematical Art">The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art</a></i=
>. Its use is illustrated in eighteen problems, with two to five equations.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systems_of_linear_equations=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Systems of linear equations">Systems of li=
near equations</a> arose in Europe with the introduction in 1637 by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 D=
escartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coordinates">coordinates</a>=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">g=
eometry</a>. In fact, in this new geometry, now called <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_geometry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Car=
tesian geometry">Cartesian geometry</a>, lines and planes are represented b=
y linear equations, and computing their intersections amounts to solving sy=
stems of linear equations.
</p><p>The first systematic methods for solving linear systems used <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant">determ=
inants</a> and were first considered by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Leibni=
z</a> in 1693. In 1750, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel_Cr=
amer" title=3D"Gabriel Cramer">Gabriel Cramer</a> used them for giving expl=
icit solutions of linear systems, now called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cramer%27s_rule" title=3D"Cramer's rule">Cramer's rule</a>. Late=
r, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Gauss">Gauss</a> further described the method of elimination, which =
was initially listed as an advancement in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Geodesy" title=3D"Geodesy">geodesy</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Vitulli,=
_Marie_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
near_algebra#cite_note-Vitulli,_Marie-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1844 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Grassmann" =
title=3D"Hermann Grassmann">Hermann Grassmann</a> published his "Theory of =
Extension" which included foundational new topics of what is today called l=
inear algebra. In 1848, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Jose=
ph_Sylvester" title=3D"James Joseph Sylvester">James Joseph Sylvester</a> i=
ntroduced the term <i>matrix</i>, which is Latin for <i>womb</i>.
</p><p>Linear algebra grew with ideas noted in the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Complex_plane" title=3D"Complex plane">complex plane</a>. =
For instance, two numbers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">w</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">z</span> in <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><=
