 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-6"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The term <i>vector</i> was introduced as <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b=
> =3D <i>x</i><b>i</b> + <i>y</i><b>j</b> + <i>z</i><b>k</b></span> represe=
nting a point in space. The quaternion difference <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>p</i> =E2=80=93 <i>q</i></span> also produces a segment equipollent to <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>pq</i></=
span></span>. Other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypercomplex_n=
umber" title=3D"Hypercomplex number">hypercomplex number</a> systems also u=
sed the idea of a linear space with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Basis_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (linear algebra)">basis</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Cayley" title=3D"Art=
hur Cayley">Arthur Cayley</a> introduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Matrix_multiplication" title=3D"Matrix multiplication">matrix multip=
lication</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_matri=
x" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inverse matrix">inverse matrix</a> in 185=
6, making possible the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_lin=
ear_group" title=3D"General linear group">general linear group</a>. The mec=
hanism of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_representation" ti=
tle=3D"Group representation">group representation</a> became available for =
describing complex and hypercomplex numbers. Crucially, Cayley used a singl=
e letter to denote a matrix, thus treating a matrix as an aggregate object.=
 He also realized the connection between matrices and determinants and wrot=
e "There would be many things to say about this theory of matrices which sh=
ould, it seems to me, precede the theory of determinants".<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Vitulli,_Marie_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-Vitulli,_Marie-5"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Peirce" title=3D"B=
enjamin Peirce">Benjamin Peirce</a> published his <i>Linear Associative Alg=
ebra</i> (1872), and his son <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charl=
es_Sanders_Peirce" title=3D"Charles Sanders Peirce">Charles Sanders Peirce<=
/a> extended the work later.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-7"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telegraph" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Telegraph">telegraph</a> required an explanatory system,=
 and the 1873 publication by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James=
_Clerk_Maxwell" title=3D"James Clerk Maxwell">James Clerk Maxwell</a> of <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Treatise_on_Electricity_and_Mag=
netism" title=3D"A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism">A Treatise on Ele=
ctricity and Magnetism</a></i> instituted a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Field_theory_(physics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Field theo=
ry (physics)">field theory</a> of forces and required <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">=
differential geometry</a> for expression. Linear algebra is flat differenti=
al geometry and serves in tangent spaces to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Manifold" title=3D"Manifold">manifolds</a>. Electromagnetic symme=
tries of spacetime are expressed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Lorentz_transformation" title=3D"Lorentz transformation">Lorentz tran=
sformations</a>, and much of the history of linear algebra is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Lorentz_transformations" title=
=3D"History of Lorentz transformations">history of Lorentz transformations<=
/a>.
</p><p>The first modern and more precise definition of a vector space was i=
ntroduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peano" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Peano">Peano</a> in 1888;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Vitulli,_Mari=
e_5-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_=
algebra#cite_note-Vitulli,_Marie-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> by 1900, a theory of linear =
transformations of finite-dimensional vector spaces had emerged. Linear alg=
ebra took its modern form in the first half of the twentieth century when m=
any ideas and methods of previous centuries were generalized as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">=
abstract algebra</a>. The development of computers led to increased researc=
h in efficient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D=
"Algorithm">algorithms</a> for Gaussian elimination and matrix decompositio=
ns, and linear algebra became an essential tool for modeling and simulation=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Vitulli,_Marie_5-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-Vitulli,_Marie-5"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Vector_spaces">Vector space=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_alg=
ebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Vector space=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=
=3D"Vector space">Vector space</a></div>
<p>Until the 19th century, linear algebra was introduced through <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systems_of_linear_equations" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Systems of linear equations">systems of linear equations</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrices</a>. In modern mathematics, the presenta=
tion through <i>vector spaces</i> is generally preferred, since it is more =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthetic_geometry" title=3D"Synth=
etic geometry">synthetic</a>, more general (not limited to the finite-dimen=
sional case), and conceptually simpler, although more abstract.
</p><p>A vector space over a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field=
_(mathematics)" title=3D"Field (mathematics)">field</a> <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>F</i></span> (often the field of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> or of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex num=
ber">complex numbers</a>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set=
_(mathematics)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">set</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>V</i></span> equipped with two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Binary_operation" title=3D"Binary operation">binary operations</a>. <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Element_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Element (mathematics)">Elements</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>V</i></span> are called <i>vectors</i>, and elements of <i>F</i> are c=
alled <i>scalars</i>. The first operation, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Vector_addition" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vector addition=
">vector addition</a></i>, takes any two vectors <span class=3D"texhtml"><b=
>v</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>w</b></span> and outputs a thi=
rd vector <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b> + <b>w</b></span>. The second op=
eration, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_multiplication"=
 title=3D"Scalar multiplication">scalar multiplication</a></i>, takes any s=
calar <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and any vector <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> and outputs a new <span class=3D"nowrap">vector <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><b>v</b></span></span>. The axioms that addi=
tion and scalar multiplication must satisfy are the following. (In the list=
 below, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>u</b>, <b>v</b></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>w</b></span> are arbitrary elements of <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>V</i></span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> are arbitrary scalars in the field <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i></span>.)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-8"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
