s=3D"texhtml">1</span> denotes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Multiplicative_identity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multiplicative ide=
ntity">multiplicative identity</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">F</span>.
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<p>The first four axioms mean that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i></span> =
is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abelian_group" title=3D"Abel=
ian group">abelian group</a> under addition.
</p><p>The elements of a specific vector space may have various natures; fo=
r example, they could be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuple" ti=
tle=3D"Tuple">tuples</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequence=
" title=3D"Sequence">sequences</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">functions</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_ring" title=3D"Polynomia=
l ring">polynomials</a>, or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matr=
ix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrices</a>. Linear algeb=
ra is concerned with the properties of such objects that are common to all =
vector spaces.
</p>
