me vector space, a linear map <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>&nbsp;: <i>V<=
/i> =E2=86=92 <i>V</i></span> is also known as a <i>linear operator</i> on =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span>.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bijective" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Bijective">bijective</a> linear map between two vector spa=
ces (that is, every vector from the second space is associated with exactly=
 one in the first) is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isomorphi=
sm" title=3D"Isomorphism">isomorphism</a>. Because an isomorphism preserves=
 linear structure, two isomorphic vector spaces are "essentially the same" =
from the linear algebra point of view, in the sense that they cannot be dis=
tinguished by using vector space properties. An essential question in linea=
r algebra is testing whether a linear map is an isomorphism or not, and, if=
 it is not an isomorphism, finding its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Range_of_a_function" title=3D"Range of a function">range</a> (or image=
) and the set of elements that are mapped to the zero vector, called the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_(linear_operator)" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Kernel (linear operator)">kernel</a> of the map. All t=
hese questions can be solved by using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gaussian_elimination" title=3D"Gaussian elimination">Gaussian eliminati=
on</a> or some variant of this <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alg=
orithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Subspaces,_span,_and_basis"=
><span id=3D"Subspaces.2C_span.2C_and_basis"></span>Subspaces, span, and ba=
sis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_a=
lgebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Subspaces,=
 span, and basis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_subspace" ti=
tle=3D"Linear subspace">Linear subspace</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Linear_span" title=3D"Linear span">Linear span</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (l=
inear algebra)">Basis (linear algebra)</a></div>
<p>The study of those subsets of vector spaces that are in themselves vecto=
r spaces under the induced operations is fundamental, similarly as for many=
 mathematical structures. These subsets are called <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Linear_subspace" title=3D"Linear subspace">linear subspace=
s</a>. More precisely, a linear subspace of a vector space <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> over a field <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span> is a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subset" title=3D"Subset">subset</a> <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span> of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> such that <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><b>u</b> + <b>v</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><b=
>u</b></span> are in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">W</span>, for every <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>u</b></span>, <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">W</span>, and every <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">a</span> in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">F</span>. (These conditions suffice for implying that <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span> is a vector spa=
ce.)
</p><p>For example, given a linear map <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>&nbs=
p;: <i>V</i> =E2=86=92 <i>W</i></span>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Image_(function)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Image (function)=
">image</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>(<i>V</i>)</span> of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span>, and the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_image" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Inverse image">inverse image</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i><sup>=
=E2=88=921</sup>(<b>0</b>)</span> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>0</b></span=
> (called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_(linear_algebra)"=
 title=3D"Kernel (linear algebra)">kernel</a> or null space), are linear su=
bspaces of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</spa=
n> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span>, =
respectively.
</p><p>Another important way of forming a subspace is to consider <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination" title=3D"Linear combi=
nation">linear combinations</a> of a set <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span> of vectors: the set of all sums=20
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
