<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>1</sub>, <b>v</b><sub>2</sub>=
, ..., <b>v</b><sub><i>k</i></sub></span> are in <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a<=
/i><sub>1</sub>, <i>a</i><sub>2</sub>, ..., <i>a</i><sub><i>k</i></sub></sp=
an> are in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</spa=
n> form a linear subspace called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Linear_span" title=3D"Linear span">span</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span>. The span of <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span> is also the intersection of =
all linear subspaces containing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">S</span>. In other words, it is the smallest (for the inclus=
ion relation) linear subspace containing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span>.
</p><p>A set of vectors is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linearl=
y_independent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linearly independent">linearl=
y independent</a> if none is in the span of the others. Equivalently, a set=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span> of vect=
ors is linearly independent if the only way to express the zero vector as a=
 linear combination of elements of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">S</span> is to take zero for every coefficient <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a<sub>i</sub></span>.
</p><p>A set of vectors that spans a vector space is called a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanning_set" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sp=
anning set">spanning set</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ge=
nerating_set" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Generating set">generating set=
</a>. If a spanning set <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">S</span> is <i>linearly dependent</i> (that is not linearly independ=
ent), then some element <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>w</b></span> of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span> is in the span o=
f the other elements of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">S</span>, and the span would remain the same if one were to remove <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><b>w</b></span> from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span>. One may continue to remove elements of=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">S</span> until g=
etting a <i>linearly independent spanning set</i>. Such a linearly independ=
ent set that spans a vector space <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">V</span> is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Basis_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (linear algebra)">basis</a> of <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i></span>. The importance of bases lies in the=
 fact that they are simultaneously minimal-generating sets and maximal inde=
pendent sets. More precisely, if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">S</span> is a linearly independent set, and <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span> is a spanning set such =
that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i> =E2=8A=86 <i>T</i></span>, then there=
 is a basis <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</sp=
an> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i> =E2=8A=86 <i>B</i> =E2=8A=86=
 <i>T</i></span>.
</p><p>Any two bases of a vector space <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i></sp=
an> have the same <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinality" tit=
