">composition</a> of the corresponding linear maps, and the product of a ma=
trix and a column matrix is the column matrix representing the result of ap=
plying the represented linear map to the represented vector. It follows tha=
t the theory of finite-dimensional vector spaces and the theory of matrices=
 are two different languages for expressing the same concepts.
</p><p>Two matrices that encode the same linear transformation in different=
 bases are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similar_(linear_=
algebra)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Similar (linear algebra)">similar<=
/a>. It can be proved that two matrices are similar if and only if one can =
transform one into the other by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El=
ementary_matrix" title=3D"Elementary matrix">elementary row and column oper=
ations</a>. For a matrix representing a linear map from <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span>, the row operations correspond t=
o change of bases in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">V</span> and the column operations correspond to change of bases in <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span>. Every matr=
ix is similar to an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_matri=
x" title=3D"Identity matrix">identity matrix</a> possibly bordered by zero =
rows and zero columns. In terms of vector spaces, this means that, for any =
linear map from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W=
</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</spa=
n>, there are bases such that a part of the basis of <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span> is mapped bijectively on a par=
t of the basis of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>V</span>, and that the remaining basis elements of <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span>, if any, are mapped to zero. <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_elimination" title=3D"Gauss=
ian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a> is the basic algorithm for findin=
g these elementary operations, and proving these results.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Linear_systems">Linear syst=
ems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_a=
lgebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Linear sys=
tems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equ=
ations" title=3D"System of linear equations">System of linear equations</a>=
</div>
<p>A finite set of linear equations in a finite set of variables, for examp=
le, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>x</i><sub>2</sub>, ...=
, <i>x<sub>n</sub></i></span>, or <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i>, <i>y</i=
>, ..., <i>z</i></span> is called a <b> system of linear equations</b> or a=
 <b>linear system</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-12"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#=
cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-15"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Systems of linear equations form a fundamental part of linear algebr=
a. Historically, linear algebra and matrix theory have been developed for s=
olving such systems. In the modern presentation of linear algebra through v=
ector spaces and matrices, many problems may be interpreted in terms of lin=
ear systems.
