f and only if the determinant is invertible (i.e., nonzero if the scalars b=
elong to a field).
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cramer%27s_rule" title=3D"C=
ramer's rule">Cramer's rule</a> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Closed-form_expression" title=3D"Closed-form expression">closed-form exp=
ression</a>, in terms of determinants, of the solution of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"System of li=
near equations">system of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">n</span> linear equations in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">n</span> unknowns</a>. Cramer's rule is useful for rea=
soning about the solution, but, except for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i>=
 =3D 2</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml">3</span>, it is rarely used for co=
mputing a solution, since <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian=
_elimination" title=3D"Gaussian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a> is a =
faster algorithm.
</p><p>The <i>determinant of an endomorphism</i> is the determinant of the =
matrix representing the endomorphism in terms of some ordered basis. This d=
efinition makes sense since this determinant is independent of the choice o=
f the basis.
</p>
