<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_form" title=3D"Linear =
form">linear form</a> is a linear map from a vector space <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> over a field <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span> to the field of sca=
lars <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span>, vi=
ewed as a vector space over itself. Equipped by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pointwise" title=3D"Pointwise">pointwise</a> addition and mul=
tiplication by a scalar, the linear forms form a vector space, called the <=
b>dual space</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">V</span>, and usually denoted <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">V*</span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-18"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V<span class=
=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></span>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_no=
te-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>1</sub>, ..., <b>v</b><sub><=
i>n</i></sub></span> is a basis of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">V</span> (this implies that <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> is finite-dimensional), then one can =
define, for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>i</i> =3D 1, ..., <i>n</i></span>, a=
 linear map <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v<sub>i</sub></i>*</span> such that =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v<sub>i</sub></i>*(<b>v</b><sub><i>i</i></sub>) =
=3D 1</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v<sub>i</sub></i>*(<b>v</b><sub=
><i>j</i></sub>) =3D 0</span> if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>j</i> =E2=89=A0=
 <i>i</i></span>. These linear maps form a basis of <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>V</i>*</span>, called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual=
_basis" title=3D"Dual basis">dual basis</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v=
</b><sub>1</sub>, ..., <b>v</b><sub><i>n</i></sub></span>. (If <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> is not finite-dimen=
sional, the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>v<sub>i</sub></i>*</span> may be def=
ined similarly; they are linearly independent, but do not form a basis.)
</p><p>For <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> in <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span>, the map
</p>
