</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relationship_with_geometry"=
>Relationship with geometry</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=
=3D"Edit section: Relationship with geometry"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There is a strong relationship between linear algebra and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geometry</a>, which=
 started with the introduction by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a>,=
 in 1637, of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinates=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cartesian coordinates">Cartesian coordinat=
es</a>. In this new (at that time) geometry, now called <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_geometry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ca=
rtesian geometry">Cartesian geometry</a>, points are represented by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinates" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Cartesian coordinates">Cartesian coordinates</a>, which are se=
quences of three real numbers (in the case of the usual <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional_space" title=3D"Three-dimensional s=
pace">three-dimensional space</a>). The basic objects of geometry, which ar=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (=
geometry)">lines</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(ge=
ometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane (geometry)">planes</a> are re=
presented by linear equations. Thus, computing intersections of lines and p=
lanes amounts to solving systems of linear equations. This was one of the m=
ain motivations for developing linear algebra.
</p><p>Most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_transformati=
on" title=3D"Geometric transformation">geometric transformation</a>, such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Translation_(geometry)" title=3D=
"Translation (geometry)">translations</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Rotation" title=3D"Rotation">rotations</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_(mathematics)" title=3D"Reflection (mathemati=
cs)">reflections</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigid_motion=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rigid motion">rigid motions</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isometry" title=3D"Isometry">isometries</=
a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projection_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Projection (mathematics)">projections</a> transform lines into lin=
es. It follows that they can be defined, specified, and studied in terms of=
 linear maps. This is also the case of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Homography" title=3D"Homography">homographies</a> and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_transformation" title=3D"M=C3=B6bius t=
ransformation">M=C3=B6bius transformations</a> when considered as transform=
ations of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_space" titl=
e=3D"Projective space">projective space</a>.
</p><p>Until the end of the 19th century, geometric spaces were defined by =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axioms</a> =
relating points, lines, and planes (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Synthetic_geometry" title=3D"Synthetic geometry">synthetic geometry</a>).=
 Around this date, it appeared that one may also define geometric spaces by=
 constructions involving vector spaces (see, for example, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_space" title=3D"Projective space">Projec=
tive space</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_space" t=
itle=3D"Affine space">Affine space</a>). It has been shown that the two app=
roaches are essentially equivalent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-23"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> In classical geometry, the involved vector spaces are vector spa=
ces over the reals, but the constructions may be extended to vector spaces =
over any field, allowing considering geometry over arbitrary fields, includ=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_field" title=3D"Finite =
field">finite fields</a>.
</p><p>Presently, most textbooks introduce geometric spaces from linear alg=
ebra, and geometry is often presented, at the elementary level, as a subfie=
ld of linear algebra.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Usage_and_applications">Usa=
ge and applications<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Applications"></span></h2><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</spa=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Usage and applicat=
ions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>Linear algebra is used in almost all areas of mathematics, thus making i=
t relevant in almost all scientific domains that use mathematics. These app=
lications may be divided into several wide categories.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Functional_analysis">Functi=
onal analysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section=
: Functional analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analysis" title=3D"F=
unctional analysis">Functional analysis</a> studies <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Function_space" title=3D"Function space">function spaces<=
/a>. These are vector spaces with additional structure, such as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_space" title=3D"Hilbert space">Hilber=
t spaces</a>. Linear algebra is thus a fundamental part of functional analy=
sis and its applications, which include, in particular, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantu=
m mechanics</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave_function" ti=
tle=3D"Wave function">wave functions</a>) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Fourier_analysis" title=3D"Fourier analysis">Fourier analysis</=
a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_basis" title=3D"Ort=
hogonal basis">orthogonal basis</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Scientific_computation">Sci=
entific computation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Scientific computation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Nearly all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_computati=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scientific computation">scientific compu=
tations</a> involve linear algebra. Consequently, linear algebra algorithms=
 have been highly optimized. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic=
_Linear_Algebra_Subprograms" title=3D"Basic Linear Algebra Subprograms">BLA=
S</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LAPACK" title=3D"LAPACK"=
>LAPACK</a> are the best known implementations. For improving efficiency, s=
ome of them configure the algorithms automatically, at run time, to adapt t=
hem to the specificities of the computer (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Cache_(computing)" title=3D"Cache (computing)">cache</a> size, numb=
er of available <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-core_process=
or" title=3D"Multi-core processor">cores</a>,&nbsp;...).
</p><p>Since the 1960s there have been processors with specialized instruct=
ions<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for optimizing the o=
perations of linear algebra, optional array processors<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_alge=
bra#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> under the control of a conventional processor=
, supercomputers<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Star100HW_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-Star100HW-27"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-cray1hw_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-cray1hw-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> designed for arr=
ay processing and conventional processors augmented<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra=
#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> with vector registers.
</p><p>Some contemporary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Processor=
_(computing)" title=3D"Processor (computing)">processors</a>, typically <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphics_processing_units" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Graphics processing units">graphics processing units</=
a> (GPU), are designed with a matrix structure, for optimizing the operatio=
ns of linear algebra.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometry_of_ambient_space">=
Geometry of ambient space</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"E=
dit section: Geometry of ambient space"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_model" title=
=3D"Mathematical model">modeling</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Ambient_space" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ambient space">ambient =
space</a> is based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" ti=
tle=3D"Geometry">geometry</a>. Sciences concerned with this space use geome=
try widely. This is the case with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mechanics" title=3D"Mechanics">mechanics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Robotics" title=3D"Robotics">robotics</a>, for describing <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigid_body_dynamics" title=3D"Rigid =
body dynamics">rigid body dynamics</a>; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Geodesy" title=3D"Geodesy">geodesy</a> for describing <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth_shape" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Earth=
 shape">Earth shape</a>; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perspecti=
vity" title=3D"Perspectivity">perspectivity</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Computer_vision" title=3D"Computer vision">computer vision</=
a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_graphics" title=
=3D"Computer graphics">computer graphics</a>, for describing the relationsh=
ip between a scene and its plane representation; and many other scientific =
domains.
</p><p>In all these applications, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Synthetic_geometry" title=3D"Synthetic geometry">synthetic geometry</a> is =
often used for general descriptions and a qualitative approach, but for the=
 study of explicit situations, one must compute with <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coordinates"=
>coordinates</a>. This requires the heavy use of linear algebra.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Study_of_complex_systems">S=
tudy of complex systems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Study of complex systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_system" title=3D=
"Complex system">Complex system</a></div>
<p>Most physical phenomena are modeled by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Partial_differential_equation" title=3D"Partial differential equati=
on">partial differential equations</a>. To solve them, one usually decompos=
es the space in which the solutions are searched into small, mutually inter=
acting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discretization" title=3D"Di=
scretization">cells</a>. For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linea=
r_system" title=3D"Linear system">linear systems</a> this interaction invol=
ves <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_function" title=3D"Line=
ar function">linear functions</a>. For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Nonlinear_systems" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Nonlinear systems">n=
onlinear systems</a>, this interaction is often approximated by linear func=
tions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>This is called a lin=
ear model or first-order approximation. Linear models are frequently used f=
or complex nonlinear real-world systems because they make <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parametrization_(geometry)" title=3D"Parametrizatio=
n (geometry)">parametrization</a> more manageable.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#=
cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> In both cases, very large matrices are generally =
involved. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weather_forecasting" tit=
le=3D"Weather forecasting">Weather forecasting</a> (or more specifically, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parametrization_(atmospheric_modeli=
ng)" title=3D"Parametrization (atmospheric modeling)">parametrization for a=
tmospheric modeling</a>) is a typical example of a real-world application, =
where the whole Earth <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere" =
title=3D"Atmosphere">atmosphere</a> is divided into cells of, say, 100&nbsp=
;km of width and 100&nbsp;km of height.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fluid_mechanics,_fluid_dyna=
mics,_and_thermal_energy_systems"><span id=3D"Fluid_mechanics.2C_fluid_dyna=
mics.2C_and_thermal_energy_systems"></span>Fluid mechanics, fluid dynamics,=
 and thermal energy systems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Edit section: Fluid mechanics, fluid dynamics, and thermal energy syste=
ms"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algeb=
ra#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#cite_note-35"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>Linear algebra, a branch of mathematics dealing with <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_spaces" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vec=
tor spaces">vector spaces</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Linear_mapping" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear mapping">linear mappi=
ngs</a> between these spaces, plays a critical role in various engineering =
disciplines, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_mecha=
nics" title=3D"Fluid mechanics">fluid mechanics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics" title=3D"Fluid dynamics">fluid dynamics<=
/a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_energy" title=3D"=
Thermal energy">thermal energy</a> systems. Its application in these fields=
 is multifaceted and indispensable for solving complex problems.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_mechanics" title=
=3D"Fluid mechanics">fluid mechanics</a>, linear algebra is integral to und=
erstanding and solving problems related to the behavior of fluids. It assis=
ts in the modeling and simulation of fluid flow, providing essential tools =
for the analysis of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics=
" title=3D"Fluid dynamics">fluid dynamics</a> problems. For instance, linea=
r algebraic techniques are used to solve systems of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Di=
fferential equations">differential equations</a> that describe fluid motion=
. These equations, often complex and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Non-linear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-linear">non-linear</a>, c=
an be linearized using linear algebra methods, allowing for simpler solutio=
ns and analyses.
</p><p>In the field of fluid dynamics, linear algebra finds its application=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_fluid_dynamics" =
title=3D"Computational fluid dynamics">computational fluid dynamics</a> (CF=
D), a branch that uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_a=
nalysis" title=3D"Numerical analysis">numerical analysis</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_structure" title=3D"Data structure">dat=
a structures</a> to solve and analyze problems involving fluid flows. CFD r=
elies heavily on linear algebra for the computation of fluid flow and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_transfer" title=3D"Heat transfer">=
heat transfer</a> in various applications. For example, the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navier%E2%80%93Stokes_equations" title=3D"Navier=
=E2=80=93Stokes equations">Navier=E2=80=93Stokes equations</a>, fundamental=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics" title=3D"Fluid=
 dynamics">fluid dynamics</a>, are often solved using techniques derived fr=
om linear algebra. This includes the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrices</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_(mathematics_and_physi=
cs)" title=3D"Vector (mathematics and physics)">vectors</a> to represent an=
d manipulate fluid flow fields.
</p><p>Furthermore, linear algebra plays a crucial role in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_energy" title=3D"Thermal energy">thermal e=
nergy</a> systems, particularly in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Power_systems" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Power systems">power systems=
</a> analysis. It is used to model and optimize the generation, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_power_transmission" title=3D"Electri=
c power transmission">transmission</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Electric_power_distribution" title=3D"Electric power distribution=
">distribution</a> of electric power. Linear algebraic concepts such as mat=
rix operations and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalue</a> problems are employe=
d to enhance the efficiency, reliability, and economic performance of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_systems" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Power systems">power systems</a>. The application of linear algebra =
in this context is vital for the design and operation of modern <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_systems" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Power systems">power systems</a>, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Renewable_energy" title=3D"Renewable energy">renewable energy</a=
> sources and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smart_grid" title=3D=
"Smart grid">smart grids</a>.
</p><p>Overall, the application of linear algebra in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_mechanics" title=3D"Fluid mechanics">fluid mechani=
cs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics" title=3D"F=
luid dynamics">fluid dynamics</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Thermal_energy" title=3D"Thermal energy">thermal energy</a> systems is=
 an example of the profound interconnection between <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">e=
ngineering</a>. It provides engineers with the necessary tools to model, an=
alyze, and solve complex problems in these domains, leading to advancements=
 in technology and industry.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extensions_and_generalizati=
ons">Extensions and generalizations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" =
title=3D"Edit section: Extensions and generalizations"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This section presents several related topics that do not appear generall=
y in elementary textbooks on linear algebra but are commonly considered, in=
 advanced mathematics, as parts of linear algebra.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Module_theory">Module theor=
y</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_alg=
ebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Module theo=
ry"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Module_(mathematics)=
" title=3D"Module (mathematics)">Module (mathematics)</a></div>
<p>The existence of multiplicative inverses in fields is not involved in th=
e axioms defining a vector space. One may thus replace the field of scalars=
 by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D=
"Ring (mathematics)">ring</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">R</span>, and this gives the structure called a <b>module</b> =
over <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>, or=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>-module.
</p><p>The concepts of linear independence, span, basis, and linear maps (a=
lso called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Module_homomorphism" ti=
tle=3D"Module homomorphism">module homomorphisms</a>) are defined for modul=
es exactly as for vector spaces, with the essential difference that, if <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> is not a fi=
eld, there are modules that do not have any basis. The modules that have a =
basis are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_module" title=
=3D"Free module">free modules</a>, and those that are spanned by a finite s=
et are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finitely_generated_modu=
le" title=3D"Finitely generated module">finitely generated modules</a>. Mod=
ule homomorphisms between finitely generated free modules may be represente=
d by matrices. The theory of matrices over a ring is similar to that of mat=
rices over a field, except that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De=
terminant" title=3D"Determinant">determinants</a> exist only if the ring is=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_ring" title=3D"Commut=
ative ring">commutative</a>, and that a square matrix over a commutative ri=
ng is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix" title=3D"=
Invertible matrix">invertible</a> only if its determinant has a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_inverse" title=3D"Multiplicati=
ve inverse">multiplicative inverse</a> in the ring.
</p><p>Vector spaces are completely characterized by their dimension (up to=
 an isomorphism). In general, there is not such a complete classification f=
or modules, even if one restricts oneself to finitely generated modules. Ho=
wever, every module is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cokernel"=
 title=3D"Cokernel">cokernel</a> of a homomorphism of free modules.
</p><p>Modules over the integers can be identified with <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abelian_group" title=3D"Abelian group">abelian groups=
</a>, since the multiplication by an integer may be identified as a repeate=
d addition. Most of the theory of abelian groups may be extended to modules=
 over a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_ideal_domain" ti=
tle=3D"Principal ideal domain">principal ideal domain</a>. In particular, o=
ver a principal ideal domain, every submodule of a free module is free, and=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_finite=
ly_generated_abelian_groups" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fundamental the=
orem of finitely generated abelian groups">fundamental theorem of finitely =
generated abelian groups</a> may be extended straightforwardly to finitely =
generated modules over a principal ring.
</p><p>There are many rings for which there are algorithms for solving line=
ar equations and systems of linear equations. However, these algorithms hav=
e generally a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_comple=
xity" title=3D"Computational complexity">computational complexity</a> that =
is much higher than similar algorithms over a field. For more details, see =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_equation_over_a_ring" title=
=3D"Linear equation over a ring">Linear equation over a ring</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Multilinear_algebra_and_ten=
sors">Multilinear algebra and tensors</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22=
" title=3D"Edit section: Multilinear algebra and tensors"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<table class=3D"box-Cleanup plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-Cle=
anup" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"mbox-image"><div class=
=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><span><img alt=3D"" src=3D"htt=
ps://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-=
clear.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"40" height=3D"40" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"48" data-file-height=3D"48"></span></span></=
div></td><td class=3D"mbox-text"><div class=3D"mbox-text-span">This section=
 may <b>require <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Cleanup"=
 title=3D"Wikipedia:Cleanup">cleanup</a></b> to meet Wikipedia's <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style" title=3D"Wikipedi=
a:Manual of Style">quality standards</a>. The specific problem is: <b>The d=
ual space is considered above, and the section must be rewritten to give an=
 understandable summary of this subject.</b><span class=3D"hide-when-compac=
t"> Please help <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:EditPage/L=
inear_algebra" title=3D"Special:EditPage/Linear algebra">improve this secti=
on</a> if you can.</span>  <span class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=
=3D"date">September 2018</span>)</i></span><span class=3D"hide-when-compact=
"><i> (<small><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_tem=
plate_removal" title=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and wh=
en to remove this message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></=
table>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilinear_algebra" title=
=3D"Multilinear algebra">multilinear algebra</a>, one considers multivariab=
le linear transformations, that is, mappings that are linear in each of sev=
eral different variables. This line of inquiry naturally leads to the idea =
of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_space" title=3D"Dual s=
pace">dual space</a>, the vector space <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V*</i></s=
pan> consisting of linear maps <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>&nbsp;: <i>V=
</i> =E2=86=92 <i>F</i></span> where <i>F</i> is the field of scalars. Mult=
ilinear maps <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>T</i>&nbsp;: <i>V<sup>n</sup></i> =
=E2=86=92 <i>F</i></span> can be described via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Tensor_product" title=3D"Tensor product">tensor products</a> o=
f elements of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V*</i></span>.
</p><p>If, in addition to vector addition and scalar multiplication, there =
is a bilinear vector product <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i> =C3=97 <i>V</=
i> =E2=86=92 <i>V</i></span>, the vector space is called an <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra_over_a_field" title=3D"Algebra over a fie=
ld">algebra</a>; for instance, associative algebras are algebras with an as=
sociate vector product (like the algebra of square matrices, or the algebra=
 of polynomials).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Topological_vector_spaces">=
Topological vector spaces</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DLinear_algebra&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"E=
dit section: Topological vector spaces"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_vector_=
space" title=3D"Topological vector space">Topological vector space</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normed_vector_space" title=3D"Normed =
vector space">Normed vector space</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Hilbert_space" title=3D"Hilbert space">Hilbert space</a></div>
<p>Vector spaces that are not finite-dimensional often require additional s=
tructure to be tractable. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normed=
_vector_space" title=3D"Normed vector space">normed vector space</a> is a v=
ector space along with a function called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Norm_(mathematics)" title=3D"Norm (mathematics)">norm</a>, which m=
easures the "size" of elements. The norm induces a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Metric_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Metri=
c (mathematics)">metric</a>, which measures the distance between elements, =
and induces a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_space" t=
itle=3D"Topological space">topology</a>, which allows for a definition of c=
ontinuous maps. The metric also allows for a definition of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)"=
>limits</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complete_metric_sp=
ace" title=3D"Complete metric space">completeness</a> =E2=80=93 a normed ve=
ctor space that is complete is known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Banach_space" title=3D"Banach space">Banach space</a>. A complete m=
etric space along with the additional structure of an <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_product_space" title=3D"Inner product space">inne=
r product</a> (a conjugate symmetric <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Sesquilinear_form" title=3D"Sesquilinear form">sesquilinear form</a>) is=
 known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_space" title=
=3D"Hilbert space">Hilbert space</a>, which is in some sense a particularly=
 well-behaved Banach space. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functi=
onal_analysis" title=3D"Functional analysis">Functional analysis</a> applie=
s the methods of linear algebra alongside those of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">mat=
hematical analysis</a> to study various function spaces; the central object=
s of study in functional analysis are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Lp_space" title=3D"Lp space"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">L<sup>p</sup></span> spaces</a>, which are Banach spaces, a=
nd especially the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i><sup>2</sup></span> space=
 of square-integrable functions, which is the only Hilbert space among them=
. Functional analysis is of particular importance to quantum mechanics, the=
 theory of partial differential equations, digital signal processing, and e=
lectrical engineering. It also provides the foundation and theoretical fram=
ework that underlies the Fourier transform and related methods.
